
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Ideology And The Decline Of Management Theory
AU  - Nehrbass, Richard G.
Y1  - 1979/07/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1979.4289117
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1979.4289117
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 427
EP  - 431
VL  - 4
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article explores the role of ideology in the formation, development and dissemination of management theory. Organizational theorizing is often ideological and based on assumptions they may not be true. This biasing is responsible for the continuation of inappropriate managerial practices. The central belief of the ideology in question here is a faith in the inherent goodness of humanity. Quality of work life, participative management and organizational development are chosen to illustrate the effect of combining research with ideology. There is ample empirical evidence that job dissatisfaction has changed little and that significant number of workers actually prefer jobs typically defined as boring.
AB  - The article explores the role of ideology in the formation, development and dissemination of management theory. Organizational theorizing is often ideological and based on assumptions they may not be true. This biasing is responsible for the continuation of inappropriate managerial practices. The central belief of the ideology in question here is a faith in the inherent goodness of humanity. Quality of work life, participative management and organizational development are chosen to illustrate the effect of combining research with ideology. There is ample empirical evidence that job dissatisfaction has changed little and that significant number of workers actually prefer jobs typically defined as boring.
