JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 439
EP  - 442
VL  - 4
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article examines the growth and characteristics of employee stock ownership programs and trusts in U.S. corporations. These programs represent a form of deferred-compensation where employees obtain company stock that is placed in a special company trust that cannot be taxed. These programs operate as a stock bonus plan where employees increase their ownership in the company. The author suggests that these plans disperse the means of production in a manner that is more compatible with the principals of distributive justice within a capitalist economy. The author also examines how the tax benefits work in the employees favor and discusses why these plans are becoming more other profit-sharing plans.
AB  - This article examines the growth and characteristics of employee stock ownership programs and trusts in U.S. corporations. These programs represent a form of deferred-compensation where employees obtain company stock that is placed in a special company trust that cannot be taxed. These programs operate as a stock bonus plan where employees increase their ownership in the company. The author suggests that these plans disperse the means of production in a manner that is more compatible with the principals of distributive justice within a capitalist economy. The author also examines how the tax benefits work in the employees favor and discusses why these plans are becoming more other profit-sharing plans.
