TY  - JOUR
T1  - Participation In Goal-Setting Programs: An Attributional Analysis
AU  - Chacko, Thomas I.
AU  - Stone, Thomas H.
AU  - Brief, Arthur P.
Y1  - 1979/07/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1979.4289120
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1979.4289120
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 433
EP  - 438
VL  - 4
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article offers a conceptual framework to examine the multiple dimensions of goal-oriented management programs such as management by objectives through the use of attribution theory. In organizational literature, participation has most often been used to describe group decision making where the members of a group share in the problem solving and decision making process. Attribution theory, which is concerned with how people perceive the behavior or outcomes of others or of themselves, may be a useful tool to explain the processes and outcomes of goal programs and provides insights into the goal-setting process. The author examines how this theory relates to the superior-subordinate relationship.
